# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: coleman-sellers-ii
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was born in Edinburgh, Scotland on 30 March 1851 to Edward Rupert Humphreys, an English classical scholar and profound educator, and Margaret McNutt of Prince Edward Island.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He attended his father's school in Boston after coming to the United States in 1859.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] At the age of fourteen he received an appointment and passed preliminary entrance exams for the United States Naval Academy before the academy discovered he was too young to complete entrance.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He instead began working for insurance companies and was made Secretary-Treasurer of the New York Guaranty and Indemnity Company by 1872, he became superintendent shortly thereafter.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He later became superintendent of the Bayonne and Greenville Gas Light Company and attended Stevens Institute of Technology earning his degree in mechanical engineering; he graduated in 1881.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1892 he founded Humphreys & Glasgow, Engineering, London and New York with Arthur G.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys continued his career with the Pintsch Lighting Company of New York, the United Gas Improvement Company, and the Weisbach Incandescent Gas Company.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In April 1872 he married Miss Eva Guillandeu of Bergen Point, NJ.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] They had three children in total: Harold, Crombie and Dorothy Caroline Humphreys-Turnbull.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of his son Harold, who was also the first son of a Stevens alumnus to graduate from the college, he endowed the Harold Humphreys Scholarship in 1902.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of Crombie, who drowned with Harold in the Nile in 1901, the Crombie Humphreys Scholarship in 1904.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1927, Alexander Crombie Humphreys lost a battle with cancer.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] His death came two years after serving as President of his Alma mater for a quarter of a century, and chairman of the board of trustees for two years.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] The only immediate family member to outlive him was his daughter.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Following the death of Henry Morton in 1902, the board of trustees of Stevens Institute of Technology unanimously called upon Humphreys to serve his Alma mater as president.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Prior to his presidency, Humphreys was elected a trustee of the institute on 23 December 1891 and served as chair of the Stevens Alumni Association from 1883 to 1886.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys developed the institute as one of the first technical schools in the United States.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During a dinner following his inauguration, Colonel Edwin A.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, Jr., son of the school's founder Edwin A.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, presented the institute with a plot of land on which to construct a dormitory.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon assuming the office of President, Humphreys requested of Andrew Carnegie the financial support to construct a new building.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He followed this with an address to the Board of Trustees urging construction of the Morton Laboratory of Chemistry, a dormitory, a gymnasium and library – a "crying need of the Institute".
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] As a homage to his predecessor, Humphreys campaigned for the creation of the Morton Memorial Chemistry Laboratory and commissioned a book on Stevens' founding and its early years to be named in his honor.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] These initiatives were but foreshadowing of the growth Humphreys would bring to Stevens.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1924 the campus grew from just over a city block to 23-acres, enrollment quadrupled and endowment grew to $2,864,000 (from $384,800 when Humprheys took office).
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] That year also marked the successful end of the "Million Dollar Campaign", which had attracted donations from alumni as well as George Eastman and Edward Harkness.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1909, Stevens seized the opportunity to acquire Castle Point from Richard Stevens inclusive of the prominent Stevens Family Castle constructed in 1853; the purchase was primarily funded by the Carnegie Foundation and John D.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] This came within months of acquiring the land adjacent to present-day 8th street upon which fraternity houses were constructed that stand to this day.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1960 the Institute expanded again and constructed two residence halls, one of which bared his name.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the growth of the institute, Alexander C.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys felt it important to impart engineering students with a sense of business – a tool that would be essential in their success in all lines of manufacturing.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He began teaching the first courses on this topic in 1903 and is regarded as the father of Engineering Economics.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] To honor his contributions, Stevens Institute of Technology endows an Alexander Crombie Humphreys Chair in Economics of Engineering.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the dinner of his inauguration, Humphreys announced that one of his ambitions was to start an Honor System at Stevens to cover academic work.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was very adamant that the creation of such a system come from the students and on the first page of the first issue of the school newspaper "The Stute" appeared an article written by a junior urging the implementation of such.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1908 the students created a self run Honor Board who was charged with investigating cases, bringing up charges, judging cases by a vote and recommend punishments to the faculty.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon Humphreys' recommendation, faculty were also required to abide by such a pledge in administering exams within Honor Board guidelines on the grounds that it is a "...proviso apply[ing] to the examiner as well as to the student".
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-graham-christie] Christie was born in Manchester, Ontario, Canada to Peter Christie and Mary Honor (Graham) Christie.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-graham-christie] He obtained his MSc in mechanical engineering at the School of Practical Science at the University of Toronto in 1901.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-graham-christie] After his graduation Christie started as an apprentice in the engineering shop of the Westinghouse Machine Company.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-graham-christie] After the introduction of its first steam turbine, Christie specialized in that field.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-graham-christie] By 1909 he was research Assistant in Steam and Gas Engineering at the University of Wisconsin, and associate professor of Steam and Gas Engineering by 1914.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-graham-christie] In 1914 he moved to the Johns Hopkins University, where he became associate professor, and later Professor of Engineering until his retirement in 1948, and director of the McCoy College until 1953.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-graham-christie] In 1939-40 Christie served as president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-graham-christie] He was awarded the honorary doctor in engineering by the Stevens Institute of Technology in 1939, and by the Lehigh University in 1940.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-graham-christie] The American Society for Engineering Education awarded Christie the Lamme Gold Medal in 1948, and the first George Westinghouse Gold Medal for engineering by the ASME in 1953.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/alexander-graham-christie] At the Johns Hopkins Whiting school of Engineer an annual lecture is held on his behalf, the Alexander Graham Christie Lecture.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/asme] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Sellers was born in Upper Darby Township, Pennsylvania, as the youngest son of Coleman and Sophonisba (Peale) Sellers and a direct descendant of Samuel Sellers, who in 1682 received one of the first grants of land in Pennsylvania.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] His father and a number of paternal ancestors had been engineers; his maternal grandfather was Charles Willson Peale.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] He was educated at common schools and studied for five years with Anthony Bolmar at his academy in West Chester, Pennsylvania.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] In 1846, Sellers became draughtsman in the Globe Rolling Mill in Cincinnati, Ohio, which was operated by his two older brothers, Charles and George Escol Sellers.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Here his mechanical ingenuity quickly asserted itself and under his direction the wire mill belonging to the plant was rebuilt and improved.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] He remained there for three years, serving part of the time as superintendent.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Because of his prompt and thorough investigation of scientific discoveries, he became the mentor of a group of intellectual men in Cincinnati and frequently gave lectures, illustrated by practical experiments, on chemistry, physics, and electricity.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] In 1850-1851, he undertook the design and construction of locomotives for the Panama Railroad and upon the completion of this contract, took charge of the locomotive works of James and Jonathan Niles in Cincinnati.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] He served for five years as foreman in the works of Niles and Company.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] In 1856, Sellers moved to Philadelphia, where he joined the staff of William Sellers & Co.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] (the senior partner of which was his second cousin, William Sellers), makers of machinists' tools, and general millwrights; after some years as the superintendent of the drawing office, he became chief engineer.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] In this capacity he obtained patents for a variety of inventions, some of which are listed below.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] In 1873, he became a partner of the firm.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] In 1872, Sellers was elected as a member to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Failing health led Sellers to resign his position as chief engineer of William Sellers & Co. in 1886, but he subsequently continued to engage in active practice as a consulting engineer.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Probably his greatest work in this capacity was in connection with the hydroelectric power development of Niagara Falls.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Sellers was a consulting engineer of the Cataract Construction Company, a corporation formed to execute the Niagara Falls project, and served on the International Niagara Commission, which determined the types of turbines and generators and the methods of power transmission finally adopted.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Sellers designed the first large dynamos installed in the Niagara Falls power plant.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] From the time of his return to Philadelphia in 1856, Sellers was closely identified with the Franklin Institute, of which he served as vice president for several years and as president for five consecutive terms from 1870 to 1875.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] He was appointed professor of mechanics at the Institute in 1881.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] He contributed much to the interest of the Institute's meetings by his lectures, always drawing large audiences.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] In 1888, Sellers was appointed professor of engineering practice at Stevens Institute of Technology, Hoboken, New Jersey, where he delivered lectures at intervals during the school year.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] The Institute conferred upon him the degree of doctor of engineering the same year of his appointment to the faculty.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Sellers was a member of engineering and scientific societies both in the United States and in Europe, and was a charter member and served as president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] In 1877, Sellers was decorated by King Oscar II of Sweden and Norway with the Order of St.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Olav, in honor of his scientific attainments.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Jessie married Sabin Colton, a prominent investor in Philadelphia and New York.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Coleman Sellers II died December 28, 1907, in Philadelphia and is interred at West Laurel Hill Cemetery in Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] Sellers obtained more than thirty letters-patent for inventions of his own, one of the first of which, a coupling device for shafting (1857), is the essential factor in the modern system of interchangeable shafting parts.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] In 1861, he patented the Kinematoscope (United States Patent 31357), a protean development in the history of film.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] His invention in 1866 of feed-disks for lathes or other machine tools was the first practical solution of the problem of the infinite gradation of feeds.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] His other patents relate chiefly to improved forms of tools or modifications of existing machines.
[src:coleman-sellers-ii/coleman-sellers-ii] The use of absorbent cotton for surgical operations was recommended by him as early as 1861, and he proposed the employment of glycerine in order to keep photographic plates wet.
